981
00:35:10,350 --> 00:35:11,449
You register in Japan and Korea?

982
00:35:11,450 --> 00:35:12,749
- You register in Korea and Japan. - Yes.

983
00:35:12,750 --> 00:35:15,289
- Do you go to a district office? - Yes. A district office.

984
00:35:15,290 --> 00:35:16,649
- Really? - The parents should be witnesses.

985
00:35:16,650 --> 00:35:17,989
The witnesses should be there.

986
00:35:17,990 --> 00:35:20,259
You need witnesses in Korea as well.

987
00:35:20,260 --> 00:35:22,489
- Right. - They just need to fill the form.

988
00:35:22,490 --> 00:35:23,759
Right.

989
00:35:23,760 --> 00:35:26,060
In Japan,

990
00:35:26,300 --> 00:35:28,429
the day you get married...

991
00:35:28,430 --> 00:35:30,569
- isn't the wedding anniversary. - Then?

992
00:35:30,570 --> 00:35:31,739
The day you register your marriage...

993
00:35:31,740 --> 00:35:32,946
- is the day. - The day you fill in the forms?

994
00:35:32,970 --> 00:35:34,509
That's the day...

995
00:35:34,510 --> 00:35:36,609
- you really got married. - That's the day.

996
00:35:36,610 --> 00:35:37,779
- What about Joo Ho? - That...

997
00:35:37,780 --> 00:35:39,139
Since I'm Korean,

998
00:35:39,140 --> 00:35:41,740
I was going to register the marriage and have a wedding ceremony.

999
00:35:41,880 --> 00:35:44,650
But my wife said, "We don't need to register our marriage..."

1000
00:35:45,180 --> 00:35:46,479
"or have a wedding ceremony."

1001
00:35:46,480 --> 00:35:48,489
- She had a foreigner's mindset. - What was the reason?

1002
00:35:48,490 --> 00:35:49,949
I don't think it's a foreigner's mindset.

1003
00:35:49,950 --> 00:35:51,470
- I think that's her mindset. - Is it?

1004
00:35:51,660 --> 00:35:53,059
That's what I felt at the time.

1005
00:35:53,060 --> 00:35:55,429
She said, "This is all meaningless..."

1006
00:35:55,430 --> 00:35:57,899
"if we break up."

1007
00:35:57,900 --> 00:35:59,360
"So, we don't need to do it,"

1008
00:35:59,630 --> 00:36:00,969
"and if we need to, we can do it when the need arises."

1009
00:36:00,970 --> 00:36:02,169
- "That's not what's important." - Still.

1010
00:36:02,170 --> 00:36:03,299
- "That's not what's important." - But...

1011
00:36:03,300 --> 00:36:05,399
That was dumb of you. Even if she said that...

1012
00:36:05,400 --> 00:36:07,439
- You should have still done it. - You should have celebrated it.

1013
00:36:07,440 --> 00:36:09,309
- What do you think is right? - She said it was meaningless.

1014
00:36:09,310 --> 00:36:11,339
- Who do we have to ask? - According to her perspective...

1015
00:36:11,340 --> 00:36:12,939
- What's important... - Who should we ask?

1016
00:36:12,940 --> 00:36:14,509
- is that the two of you live well. - Right.

1017
00:36:14,510 --> 00:36:16,710
- Someone, please explain. - She didn't want a wedding.

1018
00:36:16,880 --> 00:36:18,219
She said she really didn't want a wedding.

1019
00:36:18,220 --> 00:36:20,349
- I thought she was joking. - She's a realist.

1020
00:36:20,350 --> 00:36:22,219
- Someone, please explain. - She didn't want to stand...

1021
00:36:22,220 --> 00:36:24,119
in front of people at the wedding.

1022
00:36:24,120 --> 00:36:26,020
- Still. - She really hated it.

1023
00:36:26,120 --> 00:36:29,290
- Did you register your marriage? - We got registered later.

1024
00:36:29,660 --> 00:36:31,630
We registered our marriage in Switzerland too.

1025
00:36:32,430 --> 00:36:33,559
What do you think...

1026
00:36:33,560 --> 00:36:35,120
about having no wedding ceremony, June?

1027
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:38,599
That's really hard to judge.

1028
00:36:38,600 --> 00:36:42,070
- People have different values... - Values.

1029
00:36:42,240 --> 00:36:43,679
- regarding this. - That's right.

1030
00:36:43,680 --> 00:36:46,439
As for me, I had...

1031
00:36:46,440 --> 00:36:47,849
- a picture in mind. - Your fantasy.

1032
00:36:47,850 --> 00:36:50,279
- Didn't you hold a grand wedding? - As for us...

1033
00:36:50,280 --> 00:36:51,619
- Everybody came. - There were reporters.

1034
00:36:51,620 --> 00:36:54,790
Of course, there were very many reporters,

1035
00:36:55,020 --> 00:36:56,990
and we held it at a church.

1036
00:36:57,560 --> 00:36:59,559
That was in Korea.

1037
00:36:59,560 --> 00:37:02,660
The official wedding in Korea took place at a church.

1038
00:37:02,790 --> 00:37:06,300
In Canada, it happened a few months earlier.

1039
00:37:06,630 --> 00:37:09,069
We held a sort of an engagement...

1040
00:37:09,070 --> 00:37:12,240
and wedding ceremony in Canada.

1041
00:37:12,340 --> 00:37:15,440
Then we received a certification...

1042
00:37:15,810 --> 00:37:17,139
- saying we were... - You signed it.

1043
00:37:17,140 --> 00:37:18,709
- legally married. - The marriage registration.

1044
00:37:18,710 --> 00:37:20,749
When I got married,

1045
00:37:20,750 --> 00:37:22,509
there was a married life that I had imagined.

1046
00:37:22,510 --> 00:37:25,019
I wanted certain situations...

1047
00:37:25,020 --> 00:37:27,649
and a certain lifestyle.

1048
00:37:27,650 --> 00:37:30,819
I wanted my husband to do the groceries sometimes.

1049
00:37:30,820 --> 00:37:32,380
There were such pictures I had in mind.

1050
00:37:32,460 --> 00:37:34,559
But when I got married,

1051
00:37:34,560 --> 00:37:37,399
just one of those dreams came true.

1052
00:37:37,400 --> 00:37:39,900
This is what it is. I wanted...

1053
00:37:40,160 --> 00:37:43,030
to get in our wedding car...

1054
00:37:43,500 --> 00:37:47,339
wearing my wedding dress...

1055
00:37:47,340 --> 00:37:48,809
and leave like that.

1056
00:37:48,810 --> 00:37:51,240
(The moment her dream came true)

1057
00:37:51,740 --> 00:37:53,610
Only that part came true.

1058
00:37:53,780 --> 00:37:57,650
Nothing else came true.

1059
00:37:58,880 --> 00:38:00,490
What's interesting is...

1060
00:38:01,190 --> 00:38:03,890
- this is what true marriage is. - Nothing came true?

1061
00:38:04,360 --> 00:38:08,290
We all have things we hope,

1062
00:38:08,730 --> 00:38:10,089
- Right. - but when you get married,

1063
00:38:10,090 --> 00:38:11,500
they all break.

1064
00:38:11,930 --> 00:38:13,969
What I was worried about at first...

1065
00:38:13,970 --> 00:38:16,600
was that he could cause trouble...

1066
00:38:16,900 --> 00:38:18,469
because he was such a famous actor.

1067
00:38:18,470 --> 00:38:20,539
Trouble in terms of women.

1068
00:38:20,540 --> 00:38:21,769
In that area.

1069
00:38:21,770 --> 00:38:25,340
So, I was 23 years old back then,

1070
00:38:25,910 --> 00:38:29,850
and he was my first love.

1071
00:38:30,380 --> 00:38:32,279
So I thought, if this man...

1072
00:38:32,280 --> 00:38:34,720
had any issues that involved women,

1073
00:38:35,450 --> 00:38:37,389
I wouldn't be able to deal with that.

1074
00:38:37,390 --> 00:38:38,910
I thought I should just quietly leave.

1075
00:38:39,320 --> 00:38:41,489
- That's what I thought. - Quietly leave?

1076
00:38:41,490 --> 00:38:43,660
I thought I should leave with a cool attitude.

1077
00:38:43,900 --> 00:38:46,059
That's what I had in mind.

1078
00:38:46,060 --> 00:38:48,170
- You were preparing yourself. - Right.

1079
00:38:48,530 --> 00:38:51,240
I lived with him,

1080
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:54,569
but that was the only problem that didn't happen.

1081
00:38:54,570 --> 00:38:57,180
All kinds of troubles happened.

1082
00:39:01,510 --> 00:39:03,049
(Troubles that weren't on her mind happened.)

1083
00:39:03,050 --> 00:39:05,579
Everything except issues with women.

1084
00:39:05,580 --> 00:39:07,590
What June is saying is,

1085
00:39:08,050 --> 00:39:09,249
the problem...

1086
00:39:09,250 --> 00:39:10,850
- she was most worried about... - Right.

1087
00:39:10,960 --> 00:39:12,359
- didn't happen. - That didn't happen.

1088
00:39:12,360 --> 00:39:14,800
- You know what I'm saying, right? - Only that didn't happen.

1089
00:39:14,930 --> 00:39:18,059
All kinds of problems happened.

1090
00:39:18,060 --> 00:39:19,500
Whenever they happened,

1091
00:39:19,630 --> 00:39:20,830
I thought, "This isn't it."

1092
00:39:22,370 --> 00:39:23,870
"This also isn't it."

1093
00:39:25,770 --> 00:39:27,909
I lived 30 years like that.

1094
00:39:27,910 --> 00:39:32,080
It was vague for her.

1095
00:39:32,310 --> 00:39:33,980
- She had no cause to leave. - I mean...

1096
00:39:34,150 --> 00:39:38,480
Somehow, I was waiting for that one thing to happen.

1097
00:39:38,950 --> 00:39:41,519
- Women issues. - But it didn't happen.

1098
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:42,966
- It didn't happen. - It didn't happen.

1099
00:39:42,990 --> 00:39:45,619
I saw a video on YouTube...

1100
00:39:45,620 --> 00:39:48,059
where you said you would marry Min Soo even in your next life.

1101
00:39:48,060 --> 00:39:49,159
- You said that. - Right.

1102
00:39:49,160 --> 00:39:52,000
I would choose this man even in my 1,000th life.

1103
00:39:52,760 --> 00:39:53,870
Why?

1104
00:39:54,130 --> 00:39:57,200
Yoo Sung's father has a unique character.

1105
00:39:57,300 --> 00:39:58,439
- Actually, - Right.

1106
00:39:58,440 --> 00:40:02,040
He's someone who told me who he was...

1107
00:40:02,540 --> 00:40:04,079
in only three hours after we met.

1108
00:40:04,080 --> 00:40:07,849
People gave him many titles in Korea...

1109
00:40:07,850 --> 00:40:09,409
like "tough guy" and everything.

1110
00:40:09,410 --> 00:40:12,050
I think he's a true "tough guy."

1111
00:40:12,450 --> 00:40:16,690
He's really tough when he needs to be.

1112
00:40:16,890 --> 00:40:19,590
But to me,

1113
00:40:19,860 --> 00:40:21,129
- he's really gentle. - Right.

1114
00:40:21,130 --> 00:40:22,629
- He treats me well. - He's gentle to his wife.

1115
00:40:22,630 --> 00:40:24,830
I'm the only one who knows that side of him.

1116
00:40:25,200 --> 00:40:26,529
The world doesn't know.

1117
00:40:26,530 --> 00:40:29,600
So I thought there wouldn't be...

1118
00:40:29,730 --> 00:40:32,439
such an amazing man whom only I knew...

1119
00:40:32,440 --> 00:40:34,239
- That's so cool. - in this world.

1120
00:40:34,240 --> 00:40:36,140
At the time,

1121
00:40:36,940 --> 00:40:40,240
he was surrounded by such beautiful women.

1122
00:40:40,410 --> 00:40:42,449
- There were so many. - That's right.

1123
00:40:42,450 --> 00:40:45,119
- An ocean of beautiful women. - I wondered why he loved me...

1124
00:40:45,120 --> 00:40:46,279
and trusted me so much.

1125
00:40:46,280 --> 00:40:48,420
He appreciated my charm...

1126
00:40:48,520 --> 00:40:52,660
more than anyone else, and he cared about me...

1127
00:40:53,260 --> 00:40:54,590
even more than my parents.

1128
00:40:55,190 --> 00:40:56,359
- That's amazing. - That's cool.

1129
00:40:56,360 --> 00:40:58,659
- I just want to brag a little. - It's so sweet.

1130
00:40:58,660 --> 00:41:00,500
- That man... - I'd want to brag so much.

1131
00:41:00,700 --> 00:41:03,699
Said I had so much to learn from...

1132
00:41:03,700 --> 00:41:06,400
and always looked at me.

1133
00:41:06,840 --> 00:41:09,809
Of course, I would marry him 1,000 times.

1134
00:41:09,810 --> 00:41:11,010
Even if you are born again.

1135
00:41:11,480 --> 00:41:12,640
That's amazing.

1136
00:41:13,310 --> 00:41:15,750
- Then... - In the end,

1137
00:41:15,850 --> 00:41:19,849
Min Soo did a great job...

1138
00:41:19,850 --> 00:41:21,689
- Of course. - finding June.

1139
00:41:21,690 --> 00:41:24,619
- It happened really quickly. - That's right.

1140
00:41:24,620 --> 00:41:26,459
How could he find...

1141
00:41:26,460 --> 00:41:28,289
- such an amazing person... - I'm really grateful.

1142
00:41:28,290 --> 00:41:29,930
In such a short time?

1143
00:41:30,030 --> 00:41:32,129
- That's right. - Thank you so much,

1144
00:41:32,130 --> 00:41:34,599
Seo Jeong. I appreciate it.

1145
00:41:34,600 --> 00:41:35,729
- Seo Jeong. - Seo Jeong.

1146
00:41:35,730 --> 00:41:37,440
It's okay. That's about right.

1147
00:41:37,700 --> 00:41:40,269
- But... - You often speak broken Korean.

1148
00:41:40,270 --> 00:41:41,670
You can call me however you want.

1149
00:41:41,740 --> 00:41:42,839
Seo Jeong.

1150
00:41:42,840 --> 00:41:44,410
What about Hyung Tak?

1151
00:41:44,710 --> 00:41:47,209
Would you marry your current wife even if you are born again?

1152
00:41:47,210 --> 00:41:49,550
Of course.

1153
00:41:49,910 --> 00:41:51,179
- Of course. - Of course.

1154
00:41:51,180 --> 00:41:52,279
What about Joo Ho?

1155
00:41:52,280 --> 00:41:54,189
I would marry my wife again no matter what.

1156
00:41:54,190 --> 00:41:56,149
My wife was born in Argentina,

1157
00:41:56,150 --> 00:41:57,790
and I was born in Korea.

1158
00:41:59,190 --> 00:42:01,459
(They were born in opposite ends of the world...)

1159
00:42:01,460 --> 00:42:03,690
(with a 12-hour time difference.)

1160
00:42:03,890 --> 00:42:06,659
It's amazing that we're living together now.

1161
00:42:06,660 --> 00:42:07,929
That's true fate.

1162
00:42:07,930 --> 00:42:10,600
We had Na Eun, Gun Hoo, and Jin Woo.

1163
00:42:10,970 --> 00:42:12,599
We have to get married and have children...

1164
00:42:12,600 --> 00:42:14,510
to meet these three.

1165
00:42:15,170 --> 00:42:16,839
- Right. - That's why...

1166
00:42:16,840 --> 00:42:17,909
I have to get married to her again.

1167
00:42:17,910 --> 00:42:20,510
Food is also a part of culture.

1168
00:42:20,680 --> 00:42:22,709
It would be difficult to have different tastes.

1169
00:42:22,710 --> 00:42:24,849
- That would be the hardest. - Did you have trouble with that?

1170
00:42:24,850 --> 00:42:26,949
You were 23 when you got married, June.

1171
00:42:26,950 --> 00:42:28,989
You would have had no chance to make Korean food...

1172
00:42:28,990 --> 00:42:30,759
- before coming to Korea. - Didn't you practice?

1173
00:42:30,760 --> 00:42:31,760
That's right.

1174
00:42:31,761 --> 00:42:33,860
I had never made it before.

1175
00:42:33,990 --> 00:42:36,930
I met Min Soo in the last semester...

1176
00:42:37,160 --> 00:42:38,759
in university.

1177
00:42:38,760 --> 00:42:41,299
I had never cooked Korean food...

1178
00:42:41,300 --> 00:42:43,500
- in the dormitory. - Right.

1179
00:42:43,630 --> 00:42:48,170
Even more, I had never cooked rice before.

1180
00:42:48,640 --> 00:42:50,880
After I got married,

1181
00:42:51,080 --> 00:42:54,210
I realized this man should have been born 200 years ago.

1182
00:42:54,410 --> 00:42:56,580
He thought...

1183
00:42:56,880 --> 00:42:59,649
all women would be able to make Korean food.

1184
00:42:59,650 --> 00:43:01,420
He expected that.

1185
00:43:01,690 --> 00:43:03,489
At the time,

1186
00:43:03,490 --> 00:43:06,260
I heard the word "baekban..."

1187
00:43:06,690 --> 00:43:09,090
from this man.

1188
00:43:09,290 --> 00:43:11,659
I thought, "Korea is a terrible place for women."

1189
00:43:11,660 --> 00:43:12,900
One hundred side dishes?

1190
00:43:13,860 --> 00:43:16,830
- That was what baekban meant to me. - One hundred side dishes.

1191
00:43:17,800 --> 00:43:18,899
Is that why it's baekban?

1192
00:43:18,900 --> 00:43:21,569
- I thought there wouldn't be... - No.

1193
00:43:21,570 --> 00:43:23,769
- No. That wouldn't be. - a more disgusting word than that.

1194
00:43:23,770 --> 00:43:27,039
- Then, were Korean women... - Baekban.

1195
00:43:27,040 --> 00:43:29,379
- You could think like that. - supposed to make...

1196
00:43:29,380 --> 00:43:32,019
- one hundred side dishes? - Right.

1197
00:43:32,020 --> 00:43:35,249
I couldn't see the end.

1198
00:43:35,250 --> 00:43:37,490
When would I have the time to make baekban?

1199
00:43:37,720 --> 00:43:41,760
I bought a Korean cookbook written in English.

1200
00:43:42,060 --> 00:43:43,900
- That's amazing. - It was written in English.

1201
00:43:43,930 --> 00:43:45,860
I learned how to make radish soup,

1202
00:43:46,100 --> 00:43:48,769
rice, and everything.

1203
00:43:48,770 --> 00:43:51,170
I learned everything from the beginning.

1204
00:43:51,270 --> 00:43:53,840
I looked at the seasoning containers every day...

1205
00:43:54,040 --> 00:43:55,609
and wondered, "How do I make it?"

1206
00:43:55,610 --> 00:43:57,639
From 1 to 100,

1207
00:43:57,640 --> 00:44:00,209
- it was the hardest task for me. - Unbelievable.

1208
00:44:00,210 --> 00:44:02,609
The kitchen was a battlefield for me.

1209
00:44:02,610 --> 00:44:05,649
I learned and tried one thing after the next.

1210
00:44:05,650 --> 00:44:07,490
But you know how picky this man is.

1211
00:44:07,690 --> 00:44:10,650
If it didn't taste right, he told me outright.

1212
00:44:11,420 --> 00:44:13,360
- "This isn't it." - Like that.

1213
00:44:13,920 --> 00:44:15,559
"It's not like how I remember it."

1214
00:44:15,560 --> 00:44:18,859
- That must've really hurt. - It's not that one.

1215
00:44:18,860 --> 00:44:21,699
Min Soo must've been like...

1216
00:44:21,700 --> 00:44:23,469
- Dae Bal... - Dae Bal.

1217
00:44:23,470 --> 00:44:25,199
- from "What Is Love" at home. - Dae Bal.

1218
00:44:25,200 --> 00:44:27,509
- I watched... - A total patriarch.

1219
00:44:27,510 --> 00:44:29,609
Several episodes with Dae Bal in it.

1220
00:44:29,610 --> 00:44:31,139
I instantly knew it wasn't acting.

1221
00:44:31,140 --> 00:44:32,779
He was himself for real.

1222
00:44:32,780 --> 00:44:34,249
(Method acting full of real life)

1223
00:44:34,250 --> 00:44:35,879
- He wasn't acting. - Right.

1224
00:44:35,880 --> 00:44:37,979
- But many acknowledged him for it. - A patriarch.

1225
00:44:37,980 --> 00:44:41,149
When I watched it, I thought, "That's just Min Soo."

1226
00:44:41,150 --> 00:44:44,359
When it comes to rice, there's mushy rice,

1227
00:44:44,360 --> 00:44:46,359
- hard rice, - Half-cooked rice.

1228
00:44:46,360 --> 00:44:48,459
- and so forth. - Right.

1229
00:44:48,460 --> 00:44:50,329
I feared that the most.

1230
00:44:50,330 --> 00:44:53,499
After I cooked the rice and served it to Min Soo,

1231
00:44:53,500 --> 00:44:56,299
he said, "Today's rice is wrong."

1232
00:44:56,300 --> 00:44:59,269
That made me think, "What's the right rice?"

1233
00:44:59,270 --> 00:45:00,970
(What's the right rice?)

1234
00:45:01,410 --> 00:45:03,809
I can laugh with you all today.

1235
00:45:03,810 --> 00:45:05,639
- But back then, I cried... - It must've been hard.

1236
00:45:05,640 --> 00:45:07,209
In front of the rice cooker every day.

1237
00:45:07,210 --> 00:45:09,179
The rice alone was already tough.

1238
00:45:09,180 --> 00:45:11,549
And as Min Soo is an actor,

1239
00:45:11,550 --> 00:45:15,389
he eats three meals a day when not acting.

1240
00:45:15,390 --> 00:45:16,519
- Right. - When...

1241
00:45:16,520 --> 00:45:18,620
Breakfast, lunch, and dinner.

1242
00:45:18,720 --> 00:45:21,190
- He's incredible in many ways. - He won't have...

1243
00:45:21,260 --> 00:45:23,530
the same menu for the next meal.

1244
00:45:24,130 --> 00:45:28,800
I sometimes change the order of the side dishes.

1245
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:32,070
I switch places and add another sauce.

1246
00:45:32,140 --> 00:45:34,610
But he notices it right away...

1247
00:45:34,970 --> 00:45:36,440
and doesn't eat it.

1248
00:45:37,170 --> 00:45:38,279
He doesn't.

1249
00:45:38,280 --> 00:45:40,339
And snacks.

1250
00:45:40,340 --> 00:45:42,480
I have to prepare those annoying snacks.

1251
00:45:42,610 --> 00:45:44,780
Min Soo eats snacks in between meals.

1252
00:45:45,020 --> 00:45:47,279
But it's impossible to know...

1253
00:45:47,280 --> 00:45:49,620
what kind of snacks he's craving.

1254
00:45:49,650 --> 00:45:50,989
After something spicy,

1255
00:45:50,990 --> 00:45:52,859
- he might want a sweet snack... - Something sweet.

1256
00:45:52,860 --> 00:45:54,289
Or a cold one.

1257
00:45:54,290 --> 00:45:57,360
I learned the ropes.

1258
00:45:57,630 --> 00:45:59,859
Now that I've done it for 30 years,

1259
00:45:59,860 --> 00:46:00,929
(After cooking for 30 years)

1260
00:46:00,930 --> 00:46:04,669
I know my husband's appetite like the back of my hand.

1261
00:46:04,670 --> 00:46:06,999
When I ask what my husband had for lunch...

1262
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:08,809
and he tells me,

1263
00:46:08,810 --> 00:46:12,109
I know what he'll like for dinner.

1264
00:46:12,110 --> 00:46:14,409
With that, Min Soo always says,

1265
00:46:14,410 --> 00:46:17,619
"How do you know what I want, June?"

1266
00:46:17,620 --> 00:46:21,050
It's because I've been suffering for 30 years.

1267
00:46:21,150 --> 00:46:22,789
Since it's been 30 years,

1268
00:46:22,790 --> 00:46:25,790
I've become an expert in him.

1269
00:46:26,160 --> 00:46:28,759
And my husband became an expert in me.

1270
00:46:28,760 --> 00:46:31,159
That has made us...

1271
00:46:31,160 --> 00:46:33,500
into a loving couple now.

1272
00:46:33,800 --> 00:46:37,199
I never thought a day this happy could happen.

1273
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:40,799
Right. But to come this far,

1274
00:46:40,800 --> 00:46:42,910
eating habits are one thing,

1275
00:46:43,140 --> 00:46:44,679
but what about language?

1276
00:46:44,680 --> 00:46:47,039
How did you overcome the language barrier?

1277
00:46:47,040 --> 00:46:48,709
It's a challenge even to this day.

1278
00:46:48,710 --> 00:46:52,019
Compared to the past, we're doing much better.

1279
00:46:52,020 --> 00:46:54,149
- It's problematic when we fight. - When you fight.

1280
00:46:54,150 --> 00:46:56,249
There's a sudden moment when the air turns heavy...

1281
00:46:56,250 --> 00:46:59,060
in the middle of a conversation.

1282
00:46:59,190 --> 00:47:01,190
It's when I use the wrong word.

1283
00:47:01,730 --> 00:47:04,299
- When you talk in English? - When we use English.

1284
00:47:04,300 --> 00:47:06,329
- Because... - Your wife.

1285
00:47:06,330 --> 00:47:08,130
What language did she use...

1286
00:47:08,230 --> 00:47:10,500
in Switzerland other than English?

1287
00:47:10,530 --> 00:47:12,599
Switzerland doesn't have its own language.

1288
00:47:12,600 --> 00:47:15,139
The people use English, German, French, and Spanish.

1289
00:47:15,140 --> 00:47:16,239
- All four? - Yes.

1290
00:47:16,240 --> 00:47:17,240
Goodness.

1291
00:47:17,241 --> 00:47:18,779
Here's an example.

1292
00:47:18,780 --> 00:47:21,409
Something like, "You're bored, right?"

1293
00:47:21,410 --> 00:47:25,049
I was going to ask if Anna was bored.

1294
00:47:25,050 --> 00:47:28,189
But I said, "You're a boring person."

1295
00:47:28,190 --> 00:47:30,489
- That must've caused a big fight. - Right?

1296
00:47:30,490 --> 00:47:33,160
Boring and bored.

1297
00:47:33,220 --> 00:47:34,989
I mixed up the words, causing a fight.

1298
00:47:34,990 --> 00:47:37,189
I had to explain myself,

1299
00:47:37,190 --> 00:47:38,699
but the mood wasn't right.

1300
00:47:38,700 --> 00:47:40,700
At a time like that, I use a translator.

1301
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:42,769
- You use it? - Yes, right away.

1302
00:47:42,770 --> 00:47:44,199
- I show it to her... - It's hard to communicate.

1303
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:45,769
And let her know what I mean.

1304
00:47:45,770 --> 00:47:48,939
Things calm down again with time.

1305
00:47:48,940 --> 00:47:51,609
Fighting with my husband was very difficult.

1306
00:47:51,610 --> 00:47:55,880
He only talked about his side of the story,

1307
00:47:56,010 --> 00:47:57,979
regardless of whether I understood or not.

1308
00:47:57,980 --> 00:47:59,219
And that would go on for hours.

1309
00:47:59,220 --> 00:48:00,979
You know it, don't you?

1310
00:48:00,980 --> 00:48:02,589
When he starts talking, there's no end to it.

1311
00:48:02,590 --> 00:48:03,889
- Min Soo is like that. - Right?

1312
00:48:03,890 --> 00:48:06,089
I ended up forgetting the reason...

1313
00:48:06,090 --> 00:48:08,589
we started this fight.

1314
00:48:08,590 --> 00:48:10,889
Here's the idea that stuck with me.

1315
00:48:10,890 --> 00:48:13,399
Because my husband talks so much,

1316
00:48:13,400 --> 00:48:15,969
I should get a notebook...

1317
00:48:15,970 --> 00:48:18,499
and write what I want to say...

1318
00:48:18,500 --> 00:48:20,000
while he talks.

1319
00:48:20,200 --> 00:48:24,379
Then, I wouldn't forget the points I wanted to make,

1320
00:48:24,380 --> 00:48:26,140
even if my turn to speak came later.

1321
00:48:26,240 --> 00:48:28,849
When we were in an unpleasant situation,

1322
00:48:28,850 --> 00:48:31,719
- I went and got my notebook. - During a fight?

1323
00:48:31,720 --> 00:48:34,649
After that, I said, "Please talk."

1324
00:48:34,650 --> 00:48:36,789
- While fighting? - That's scary.

1325
00:48:36,790 --> 00:48:40,419
But my husband would be enraged.

1326
00:48:40,420 --> 00:48:43,529
He'd ask, "June. What are you doing right now?"

1327
00:48:43,530 --> 00:48:47,400
"Because you talk for quite a while,"

1328
00:48:47,460 --> 00:48:49,329
"I'll forget again."

1329
00:48:49,330 --> 00:48:52,499
"I'm writing whatever I want to say down."

1330
00:48:52,500 --> 00:48:55,140
His response to that was, "This isn't necessary."

1331
00:48:55,270 --> 00:48:58,339
"I'll make sure you understand everything,"

1332
00:48:58,340 --> 00:49:00,239
"so you don't have to jot down anything."

1333
00:49:00,240 --> 00:49:02,249
- He refused to listen. - I thought it wasn't easy.

1334
00:49:02,250 --> 00:49:05,879
Living such a life would be a challenge.

1335
00:49:05,880 --> 00:49:09,389
Since then, I started drawing comics.

1336
00:49:09,390 --> 00:49:11,459
I put all my words into the speech bubbles...

1337
00:49:11,460 --> 00:49:13,420
and made a comic.

1338
00:49:13,660 --> 00:49:16,629
Back then, Min Soo started shooting "Sandglass."

1339
00:49:16,630 --> 00:49:19,600
If he wasn't at home at night, I left...

1340
00:49:19,860 --> 00:49:22,170
the comic I drew on his pillow.

1341
00:49:22,400 --> 00:49:23,969
My husband would read it.

1342
00:49:23,970 --> 00:49:25,639
Everything, even curse words, was there.

1343
00:49:25,640 --> 00:49:27,539
Although my spelling was all wrong,

1344
00:49:27,540 --> 00:49:30,239
my message got through.

1345
00:49:30,240 --> 00:49:31,880
- Even curse words? - After reading that,

1346
00:49:32,310 --> 00:49:34,879
Min Soo realized I saw the whole picture...

1347
00:49:34,880 --> 00:49:36,609
and had my own stance.

1348
00:49:36,610 --> 00:49:39,179
He was deeply moved.

1349
00:49:39,180 --> 00:49:41,349
Do you still have the comics with you?

1350
00:49:41,350 --> 00:49:43,150
There's only one left.

1351
00:49:43,290 --> 00:49:47,360
(The comic June drew back then)

1352
00:49:54,770 --> 00:49:57,000
If you had kept a collection and published it,

1353
00:49:57,400 --> 00:49:59,139
it would've made a bestseller.

1354
00:49:59,140 --> 00:50:01,139
We have a different sense of humor.

1355
00:50:01,140 --> 00:50:03,309
In Korea, people say,

1356
00:50:03,310 --> 00:50:06,009
"You're so ugly."

1357
00:50:06,010 --> 00:50:07,609
- Like, "Gosh, you're so ugly." - Yes.

1358
00:50:07,610 --> 00:50:09,179
We say that even when someone is cute.

1359
00:50:09,180 --> 00:50:11,449
- Whenever Min Soo said that, - It's an ironic expression.

1360
00:50:11,450 --> 00:50:13,550
- I thought... - It must've been a shock.

1361
00:50:13,720 --> 00:50:17,820
He criticized my looks as he worked with beautiful actresses,

1362
00:50:17,860 --> 00:50:19,789
like, "Why are you so guly?"

1363
00:50:19,790 --> 00:50:21,529
- It would hurt. - That'd upset you.

1364
00:50:21,530 --> 00:50:24,129
There I thought, "How can he say that while smiling?"

1365
00:50:24,130 --> 00:50:25,630
"How heartless of him."

1366
00:50:25,960 --> 00:50:28,229
He kept calling me ugly.

1367
00:50:28,230 --> 00:50:30,729
It must feel cruel to someone who doesn't know.

1368
00:50:30,730 --> 00:50:32,399
We had such situations.

1369
00:50:32,400 --> 00:50:34,169
But later on, I realized that was...

1370
00:50:34,170 --> 00:50:35,539
- expressing affection. - An expression of love.

1371
00:50:35,540 --> 00:50:37,339
- He meant you were cute. - "How ugly."

1372
00:50:37,340 --> 00:50:38,909
- Exactly. - "You're so ugly."

1373
00:50:38,910 --> 00:50:40,680
That caused a big misunderstanding.

1374
00:50:41,180 --> 00:50:44,550
There was one time when I had the biggest fight with my wife.

1375
00:50:45,120 --> 00:50:49,289
On the day I introduced my wife to Soo Geun at the funeral hall,

1376
00:50:49,290 --> 00:50:51,989
- Did you fight that day? - I drank...

1377
00:50:51,990 --> 00:50:53,859
- Why? - until 4am.

1378
00:50:53,860 --> 00:50:56,729
As we were in the province, my wife had to drive,

1379
00:50:56,730 --> 00:50:58,760
but she couldn't understand that.

1380
00:50:59,500 --> 00:51:02,729
She said, "You shouldn't have drunk."

1381
00:51:02,730 --> 00:51:04,599
But she's not good at Korean.

1382
00:51:04,600 --> 00:51:07,369
I refuted by saying, "How is it bad that I drank?"

1383
00:51:07,370 --> 00:51:08,939
I'm sure my wife didn't understand that,

1384
00:51:08,940 --> 00:51:10,710
but I went on and on all alone.

1385
00:51:10,770 --> 00:51:12,339
There was one word that set me off.

1386
00:51:12,340 --> 00:51:13,809
- What was it? - My wife said,

1387
00:51:13,810 --> 00:51:15,280
"What's this?" in Japanese.

1388
00:51:15,910 --> 00:51:18,420
At that moment, I was like, "What?"

1389
00:51:19,020 --> 00:51:21,319
I believed it was offensive,

1390
00:51:21,320 --> 00:51:22,790
and so did my wife.

1391
00:51:23,320 --> 00:51:24,520
What's this?

1392
00:51:25,060 --> 00:51:26,260
What's this?

1393
00:51:27,390 --> 00:51:29,989
- In Japanese? - "What's this?" in Japanese.

1394
00:51:29,990 --> 00:51:31,999
(What's this?)

1395
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:33,829
The two kept going, "What's this?"

1396
00:51:33,830 --> 00:51:34,930
What's this?

1397
00:51:35,070 --> 00:51:37,769
Because there's a language barrier,

1398
00:51:37,770 --> 00:51:40,169
- the fights... - There are cultural differences.

1399
00:51:40,170 --> 00:51:42,046
- Misunderstandings are common. - We laugh it off.

1400
00:51:42,070 --> 00:51:43,739
Even the funeral culture must be different.

1401
00:51:43,740 --> 00:51:47,710
Here are the last keywords of the three.

1402
00:51:47,980 --> 00:51:51,210
First, June is on a roll with this.

1403
00:51:51,380 --> 00:51:53,920
It says, "Jennie of the home shopping world."

1404
00:51:54,120 --> 00:51:56,620
- Jennie. - Jennie of the home shopping world.

1405
00:51:56,820 --> 00:52:00,020
The annual sales are said to be 60 million dollars.

1406
00:52:00,120 --> 00:52:02,289
You made over 20 million dollars in 1 hour.

1407
00:52:02,290 --> 00:52:03,429
- Really? - In one hour?

1408
00:52:03,430 --> 00:52:05,059
Words that it happened...

1409
00:52:05,060 --> 00:52:07,129
- have been going around. - Yes.

1410
00:52:07,130 --> 00:52:08,700
I've been doing it for eight years now.

1411
00:52:08,830 --> 00:52:10,500
But I still can't believe it.

1412
00:52:10,600 --> 00:52:13,199
I'm not someone with experience...

1413
00:52:13,200 --> 00:52:14,939
to host home shopping.

1414
00:52:14,940 --> 00:52:18,139
When I was given the offer, I thought I couldn't do it.

1415
00:52:18,140 --> 00:52:20,709
I'm not skilled. That includes Korean.

1416
00:52:20,710 --> 00:52:22,750
What's more,

1417
00:52:23,050 --> 00:52:25,079
it's a two-hour live show.

1418
00:52:25,080 --> 00:52:29,290
There were times when I made slight mistakes.

1419
00:52:29,590 --> 00:52:31,659
After all, it was a live home shopping show.

1420
00:52:31,660 --> 00:52:33,489
If I were to tell you a story,

1421
00:52:33,490 --> 00:52:36,390
we had a salted seafood master on the show.

1422
00:52:36,430 --> 00:52:38,999
A male who was quite old.

1423
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:40,499
- It's already funny. - There were...

1424
00:52:40,500 --> 00:52:42,529
- I'm already worried. - various types of salted seafood.

1425
00:52:42,530 --> 00:52:44,900
And he was such a gentle master.

1426
00:52:45,370 --> 00:52:48,769
So, I said to the camera,

1427
00:52:48,770 --> 00:52:52,010
"I've tried many kinds of salted seafood,"

1428
00:52:52,340 --> 00:52:55,380
"and this master's is the best."

1429
00:52:56,850 --> 00:52:58,549
(A naughty compliment for some reason)

1430
00:52:58,550 --> 00:52:59,550
That's funny.

1431
00:52:59,551 --> 00:53:01,949
That happens. It's not a wrong expression.

1432
00:53:01,950 --> 00:53:03,189
When we talk about salted seafood,

1433
00:53:03,190 --> 00:53:05,059
you don't say the whole word.

1434
00:53:05,060 --> 00:53:07,189
- You say salted. - Yes.

1435
00:53:07,190 --> 00:53:08,629
- Right. - So I said, "I've tried..."

1436
00:53:08,630 --> 00:53:10,029
"all kinds of salted seafood,"

1437
00:53:10,030 --> 00:53:12,529
"and the best of all was the master's."

1438
00:53:12,530 --> 00:53:15,070
With our arms crossed.

1439
00:53:15,670 --> 00:53:18,069
- I was wearing an in-ear. - "In-ear."

1440
00:53:18,070 --> 00:53:19,939
- Yes. - In the in-ear,

1441
00:53:19,940 --> 00:53:22,209
the producer couldn't say anything.

1442
00:53:22,210 --> 00:53:23,869
I heard him laughing so much.

1443
00:53:23,870 --> 00:53:25,109
Yes.

1444
00:53:25,110 --> 00:53:27,339
Cameramen were...

1445
00:53:27,340 --> 00:53:29,549
- It's not exactly wrong. - The cameramen...

1446
00:53:29,550 --> 00:53:32,679
The cameramen were sitting on chairs.

1447
00:53:32,680 --> 00:53:34,619
They all fell from their chairs.

1448
00:53:34,620 --> 00:53:35,690
Right at that moment.

1449
00:53:36,220 --> 00:53:37,919
They were laughing so much.

1450
00:53:37,920 --> 00:53:40,359
I was flustered.

1451
00:53:40,360 --> 00:53:42,359
I have one more story.

1452
00:53:42,360 --> 00:53:43,929
When I first came to Korea,

1453
00:53:43,930 --> 00:53:45,700
I tried to learn...

1454
00:53:45,930 --> 00:53:48,030
the titles for married women.

1455
00:53:48,330 --> 00:53:51,229
- The titles. - And I was told...

1456
00:53:51,230 --> 00:53:52,900
"Nyeon" in Korean was...

1457
00:53:53,340 --> 00:53:54,909
a bad word.

1458
00:53:54,910 --> 00:53:57,539
You shouldn't call any women...

1459
00:53:57,540 --> 00:53:58,839
- "Nyeon." - No.

1460
00:53:58,840 --> 00:53:59,939
It wasn't appropriate.

1461
00:53:59,940 --> 00:54:02,809
But I thought there were exceptions...

1462
00:54:02,810 --> 00:54:03,810
like married "nyeon."

1463
00:54:04,210 --> 00:54:08,249
I thought I heard married "nyeon,"

1464
00:54:08,250 --> 00:54:12,389
so I thought that was okay.

1465
00:54:12,390 --> 00:54:15,289
When I was introducing myself officially,

1466
00:54:15,290 --> 00:54:17,630
I said, "Hello. I'm June Kang."

1467
00:54:18,060 --> 00:54:19,860
"I'm married 'nyeon.'"

1468
00:54:20,330 --> 00:54:23,070
I often said that.

1469
00:54:23,370 --> 00:54:26,400
Everyone froze every time.

1470
00:54:26,800 --> 00:54:29,369
This word "nyeon" was so difficult...

1471
00:54:29,370 --> 00:54:30,510
because my husband said,

1472
00:54:30,670 --> 00:54:32,710
"I shall get this relationship."

1473
00:54:33,310 --> 00:54:34,870
- "Relationship?" - Yes, so I was like,

1474
00:54:34,950 --> 00:54:36,010
"This nyeon?"

1475
00:54:36,710 --> 00:54:38,009
"What are you talking about?"

1476
00:54:38,010 --> 00:54:39,950
"Did you just call me nyeon?"

1477
00:54:40,920 --> 00:54:42,690
You thought he was disregarding you.

1478
00:54:43,220 --> 00:54:46,089
When he said, "I shall get this relationship,"

1479
00:54:46,090 --> 00:54:47,119
why was it okay for him...

1480
00:54:47,120 --> 00:54:48,160
- to say that? - Right.

1481
00:54:48,460 --> 00:54:50,829
- That slight difference. - June.

1482
00:54:50,830 --> 00:54:52,699
When you were on home shopping,

1483
00:54:52,700 --> 00:54:54,329
didn't Min Soo suddenly barge in...

1484
00:54:54,330 --> 00:54:56,129
like he did to...

1485
00:54:56,130 --> 00:54:57,429
- Yes. - Sang Min's press conference?

1486
00:54:57,430 --> 00:54:58,569
- So... - Really?

1487
00:54:58,570 --> 00:54:59,570
During the live show.

1488
00:54:59,571 --> 00:55:00,939
It was very important.

1489
00:55:00,940 --> 00:55:04,239
To be honest, I feel great responsibility...

1490
00:55:04,240 --> 00:55:06,639
- during those two hours. - Right.

1491
00:55:06,640 --> 00:55:08,249
While I was hosting,

1492
00:55:08,250 --> 00:55:09,880
on the other side of the studio,

1493
00:55:10,150 --> 00:55:12,150
I saw him entering.

1494
00:55:12,780 --> 00:55:14,320
- I saw him entering. - You saw him.

1495
00:55:14,650 --> 00:55:17,049
He was walking around...

1496
00:55:17,050 --> 00:55:19,790
when I was doing a live show.

1497
00:55:20,120 --> 00:55:23,360
There must be securities.

1498
00:55:24,490 --> 00:55:28,469
There are people who can and can't come in.

1499
00:55:28,470 --> 00:55:30,929
Why did they let him in?

1500
00:55:30,930 --> 00:55:33,240
(Why did they let him in?)

1501
00:55:33,540 --> 00:55:35,069
I started sweating.

1502
00:55:35,070 --> 00:55:37,769
So I was hoping...

1503
00:55:37,770 --> 00:55:41,010
since he was a broadcasting expert,

1504
00:55:41,310 --> 00:55:44,609
he wouldn't come in here.

1505
00:55:44,610 --> 00:55:46,849
- You doubted it. - My husband would...

1506
00:55:46,850 --> 00:55:48,149
- know that much. - Right.

1507
00:55:48,150 --> 00:55:50,750
Then he slowly started approaching me.

1508
00:55:51,190 --> 00:55:53,219
Then he stood...

1509
00:55:53,220 --> 00:55:54,419
- next to me. - Really?

1510
00:55:54,420 --> 00:55:56,459
And the stew pot.

1511
00:55:56,460 --> 00:55:58,129
- I can see him. - You know how greedy I am?

1512
00:55:58,130 --> 00:56:00,359
- Were you looking at him? - Yes.

1513
00:56:00,360 --> 00:56:01,929
- Your eyes... - You just made eye contact.

1514
00:56:01,930 --> 00:56:03,930
(Her eyes are suddenly shaking.)

1515
